  <source>Radboud University</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Survivors of a cardiac arrest frequently develop severe postanoxic encephalopathy.
      Derangements in cerebral blood after return of spontaneous circulation play an important role
      in the pathogenesis of postanoxic encephalopathy. In the present study we examine the effect
      of mild therapeutic hypothermia on cerebral blood flow and carbondioxide reactivity in
      patients after cardiac arrest.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
